Reshaping the images:¶

  • Input Shape for Dense Layers: Fashion MNIST pictures are 2D (28x28 pixels), while denser layers in a neural network require each input to be a vector (1D). Each 2D image is flattened into a 1D array so that it may be used with the thick layers.
  • Consistency: This stage makes sure that every image has the same shape and that the neural network can analyse them all equally.
In [90]:
# Flatten the images
x_train = x_train.reshape((60000, 28*28))
x_test = x_test.reshape((10000, 28*28))

Normalizing the values:¶

  • Scaling: An image's pixel values span from 0 to 255. Scaled to a narrow range input data tends to perform better for neural networks. The pixel values are scaled to the [0, 1] range by dividing by 255.
  • Convergence: By aiding in the loss function's convergence, normalisation helps to accelerate training. Similar-scale inputs cause the gradients to oscillate less during training, resulting in a faster and more stable convergence.
In [91]:
# Normalize the pixel values
x_train = x_train.astype("float32") / 255.0
x_test = x_test.astype("float32") / 255.0

One-Hot Encoding the Labels:¶

  • Multi-Class Classification: With ten classes, the Fashion MNIST dataset presents a multi-class classification challenge. Categorical integer labels are transformed into a binary matrix representation using one-hot encoding.
  • Model Compatibility: The majority of neural network architectures require the labels to be in a format that is appropriate for the loss function and the output layer.
In [92]:
# One-hot encode the labels
y_train = to_categorical(y_train, 10)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test, 10)
In [93]:
def create_model():
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(128, activation='relu'),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])
    return model

The choice of loss function: categorical_crossentropy¶

I have selected the loss function as categorical_crossentropy due to the presence of multiclass classification. Due to which we have to one-hot encode the labels of the dataset.
For sparse categorical cross-entropy integer encode labels are required.

Retraining the models to save the history of the runs for epochs and the changes and further plot the graphs for accuracy and loss comparing the performance on the training and testing sets¶

In [119]:
def create_model(activation='relu', neurons=128):
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(neurons, activation=activation),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])
    return model

def train_model(activation='relu', optimizer='rmsprop', neurons=128, epochs=10, batch_size=100):
    model = create_model(activation=activation, neurons=neurons)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch_size, validation_data=(x_test, y_test), verbose=0)
    return model, history

model_default, history_default = train_model()
model_neurons, history_neurons = train_model(neurons=500)
model_sigmoid, history_sigmoid = train_model(activation='sigmoid')
model_adam, history_adam = train_model(optimizer='adam')

def plot_model_performance(history, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title(f'{title} - Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title(f'{title} - Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')

    plt.show()

plot_model_performance(history_default, 'Default Configuration')
plot_model_performance(history_neurons, 'Increased Neurons Configuration')
plot_model_performance(history_sigmoid, 'Sigmoid Activation Configuration')
plot_model_performance(history_adam, 'Adam Optimizer Configuration')

def plot_incorrect_predictions(model, x_test, y_true, class_names, num_images=5, title=""):
    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
    predicted_classes = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
    true_classes = np.argmax(y_true, axis=1)
    incorrect_indices = np.nonzero(predicted_classes != true_classes)[0]

    plt.figure(figsize=(num_images * 2, 3)) 
    for i, incorrect in enumerate(incorrect_indices[:num_images]):
        plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(x_test[incorrect].reshape(28, 28), cmap='gray', interpolation='none')
        plt.title(f"Pred: {class_names[predicted_classes[incorrect]]}\nTrue: {class_names[true_classes[incorrect]]}", fontsize=9)
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=10, y=1.05) 
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_incorrect_predictions(model, x_test, y_test, class_names, title="Default Configuration")
plot_incorrect_predictions(modelNeurons, x_test, y_test, class_names, title="Increased Neurons Configuration")
plot_incorrect_predictions(modelActivate, x_test, y_test, class_names, title="Sigmoid Activation Configuration")
plot_incorrect_predictions(modelOptimize, x_test, y_test, class_names, title="Adam Optimizer Configuration")

Selection of the best configuration:¶

A good model is not only about high accuracy but also about how consistently it can execute (i.e., with low loss). For this reason, we should take into account both the ultimate accuracy and loss metrics when determining the optimal configuration.

  1. Default Configuration (ReLU/RMSprop): This model has lowest loss of 0.2560 and the highest accuracy of 90.61%. With a test loss of 0.3422 and a test accuracy of 87.98%, the test results show some overfitting because the model performs better on the training set than the test set.
  2. Increased Neurons (ReLU/RMSprop): Adding more neurons resulted in a 91.37% increase in accuracy and a 0.2347 decrease in loss, indicating a better model fit than the default. Additionally, the test accuracy improved to 88.55% with a significantly reduced test loss of 0.3376, outperforming the default by a small margin.
  3. Change in Activation (Sigmoid/RMSprop): Using a sigmoid activation function has resulted in a loss of 0.2989 and a reduction in accuracy to 89.09%. The least advantageous configuration results in a test accuracy of 87.40% with a greater test loss of 0.3528.
  4. Optimizer Change (ReLU/Adam): Compared to the default, using Adam as the optimizer results in a minor drop in accuracy to 89.64% and an increase in loss to 0.2877. There appears to be no apparent distinction since the test metrics remain the same as those of the default configuration.

With the highest accuracy and lowest loss on both training and test sets among all the configurations, the Increased Neurons Configuration is the best model according to the data. This implies that the model with more neurons has more successfully learned the patterns and is more broadly applicable to data that has not yet been observed.
